        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Resolving the paradox: mammon vs. issur—ownership and sanctity are separate",
      "display_title": "Mammon vs. issur",
      "timestamp": "52:22",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Rabba's response: priest cannot keep it if taken—monetary presumption holds",
          "display_title": "Rabba's answer",
          "timestamp": "52:22"
        },
        {
          "title": "But kedusha (sanctity) comes from the thing itself, not from priest's ownership",
          "display_title": "Sanctity principle",
          "timestamp": "53:44"
        },
        {
          "title": "Parallel: taking it from one owner and giving to another—both binding",
          "display_title": "Parallel case",
          "timestamp": "54:02"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "The tokfo kohen question: does hamotzi mechavero mean definitive ownership or mere doubt",
      "display_title": "Tokfo kohen",
      "timestamp": "55:22",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Rav Chanina offers proof from ma'aser behemah (animal tithe) practice",
          "display_title": "Ma'aser proof",
          "timestamp": "55:22"
        },
        {
          "title": "Safek animals from pidyon bechor (redemption) go into the tithe pool",
          "display_title": "Safek animals",
          "timestamp": "56:26"
        },
        {
          "title": "If priest could grab and keep, then owner would use doubtful animal for tithe—a problem",
          "display_title": "Tithe problem",
          "timestamp": "57:36"
        },
        {
          "title": "Abaye's refinement: works if owner has exactly ten animals, not more",
          "display_title": "Exactly ten",
          "timestamp": "60:22"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "The jumping sheep: minyan hara'uy principle and the requirement for definite tithe",
      "display_title": "Jumping sheep",
      "timestamp": "62:42",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "One sheep drops dead or jumps back in—does tithe count still work",
          "display_title": "Interruption case",
          "timestamp": "62:42"
        },
        {
          "title": "Objection: if doubt allows ממה נפשך (either way you're covered), why not here",
          "display_title": "Either-way objection",
          "timestamp": "63:39"
        },
        {
          "title": "Minyan hara'uy: animals in a valid counting are exempt even if process cuts short",
          "display_title": "Minyan hara'uy",
          "timestamp": "65:59"
        },
        {
          "title": "Answer: Torah requires definite tenth, not doubtful tenth—even with ממה נפשך",
          "display_title": "Definite tenth",
          "timestamp": "68:45"
        },
        {
          "title": "Conclusion: hamotzi mechavero means definitive presumption, not mere uncertainty",
          "display_title": "Definitive presumption",
          "timestamp": "69:15"
        }
      ]
